<br>
Despite your anecdotal evidence,IRS data show that more than 93 percent of taxable estates in 2001 were valued at less than $5 million. Farm and family-owned business assets accounted for less than three percent of the total value of these taxable estates in 2001. Because of your area, you may see more of this than other areas of the country, this doesn't, however make it common. Further, without going into it, there are substantial breaks in estate tax law aimed specifically at farms.  No one can help those who don't plan appropriately for their own death.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;If someone saves assests over time then they've paid taxes on them. <br>
<br>
This is a common misconception.  Much of the value of assets passed by bequest is usually in the form of asset appreciation or capital gain.  That is value that has *never* been taxed.  It's also value that would be taxed if you transferred that asset in any other way while still living, whether sale or an outright gift.  The estate tax is simply an extension of other rules already in our tax code, not a departure from them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1658<br> <font color=#333333>(4/27/05 8:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=130>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> more good stuff on estate tax</span><hr size=1> For family farms, repeal of the estate tax would actually increase, not decrease tax liability for those heirs that choose to sell or liquidate their portion.  With the estate tax repeal,the basis cost of the transferred asset will remain the cost at which that asset was acquired by the deceased for the purposes of capital gains.  So instead of an heir paying estate tax on only the portion of the estate outside the exemption, an heir who sells or gifts their inherited property would be liable for capital gains on the entire amount of the gain. Carrying this tax basis forward through an asset transfer upon death also introduces numerous opportunities to cheat, and needless additional complexity.<br>
<br>
Translation from tax geek speak:  this isn't about saving farmers or small business owners from paying estate tax. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kurakaikhan>Kurakai Khan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 888<br> <font color=#333333>(4/27/05 8:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=131>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: more good stuff on estate tax</span><hr size=1> It's about soaking the wealthy, yes we understand your point of view.<br>
